00:18:33,638 --> 00:18:35,338
[Yung-suk] I just found something amazing.

482
00:18:35,405 --> 00:18:36,538
STRAIGHT INTO SEO-JIN'S ROOM

483
00:18:36,605 --> 00:18:37,771
Seo-jin, open the door.

484
00:18:38,738 --> 00:18:39,805
I found something amazing.

485
00:18:39,871 --> 00:18:41,171
SEO-JIN LOOKS STRANGELY TROUBLED

486
00:18:41,971 --> 00:18:43,771
[chuckling] This is Seo-jin's room.

487
00:18:43,838 --> 00:18:45,938
- We pulled back the covers…
- Yes.

488
00:18:46,005 --> 00:18:47,771
…and found a bloodstain.

489
00:18:47,838 --> 00:18:49,771
- [Seo-jin] A bloodstain?
- [Dae-ju] Come and look.

490
00:18:50,338 --> 00:18:52,305
You can see stains here too.

491
00:18:52,371 --> 00:18:55,971
[Yung-suk] Unbelievable.
It's exactly the vibe I imagined.

492
00:18:56,038 --> 00:18:57,105
MOST LIKELY FOOD STAINS,

493
00:18:57,171 --> 00:18:58,938
BUT THAT DOESN'T MATTER
TO YUNG-SUK RIGHT NOW

494
00:18:59,005 --> 00:19:00,538
Why is this room so cold?

495
00:19:00,605 --> 00:19:02,238
[Yung-suk] So exciting. I love it here.

496
00:19:02,305 --> 00:19:03,771
[Dae-ju] It's kind of cozy.

497
00:19:03,838 --> 00:19:05,471
What do you mean? The heater is broken.

498
00:19:05,538 --> 00:19:06,871
SUFFERING SO YUNG-SUK CAN LIVE HIS DREAM

499
00:19:06,938 --> 00:19:07,771
[Yung-suk] So funny.

500
00:19:07,838 --> 00:19:09,305
Grab a drink, Seo-jin.

501
00:19:09,371 --> 00:19:10,771
Come have a beer with me.

502
00:19:10,838 --> 00:19:11,805
That made me laugh.

503
00:19:11,871 --> 00:19:13,005
ESCAPE TO YUNG-SUK'S ROOM…

504
00:19:13,071 --> 00:19:14,905
- [knock on door]
- [Yung-suk] Come in.

505
00:19:16,605 --> 00:19:19,105
- You got the ice.
- [Dae-ju] I brought a ton of it.

506
00:19:19,171 --> 00:19:22,405
It usually happens when you get the ice
or go to use the vending machine.

507
00:19:22,471 --> 00:19:24,505
It's on the way back
that you meet the bad guys

508
00:19:24,571 --> 00:19:28,705
who follow you to your room
and barge in to get you.

509
00:19:28,771 --> 00:19:29,938
THE NEVER-ENDING MOTEL CLICHÉ

510
00:19:30,005 --> 00:19:31,938
[Yung-suk] Didn't you sleep
in places like this in college?

511
00:19:32,005 --> 00:19:33,571
LEE SEO-JIN
NEW YORK UNIVERSITY GRADUATE

512
00:19:33,638 --> 00:19:35,605
I went to Boston with my friends

513
00:19:35,671 --> 00:19:37,005
- on a fishing trip.
- [Yung-suk] That's right.

514
00:19:37,071 --> 00:19:39,538
- You said you liked fishing.
- Yes, we've set off.

515
00:19:39,605 --> 00:19:43,971
We didn't even use maps
and didn't have cell phones.

516
00:19:44,038 --> 00:19:48,338
So we just followed the water trails.

517
00:19:48,971 --> 00:19:52,605
We went for two hours,
only to end up close to home.

518
00:19:52,671 --> 00:19:54,405
[Yung-suk] You ended up back at home?

519
00:19:54,471 --> 00:19:55,338
- [both laugh]
- We circled back.

520
00:19:55,405 --> 00:19:56,505
STRONG HOMING INSTINCT

521
00:19:56,571 --> 00:20:00,438
But my friends refused to go back home
since we'd come so far.

522
00:20:00,505 --> 00:20:03,038
We ended up sleeping in a local motel.

523
00:20:03,105 --> 00:20:06,405
We sat on the floor
and ate five packets of Neoguri.

524
00:20:06,471 --> 00:20:08,571
THE ONLY THING THEY CAUGHT WAS NEOGURI

525
00:20:08,638 --> 00:20:10,038
MUNCH

526
00:20:10,105 --> 00:20:11,805
HAVING BEER WITH BEEF JERKY

527
00:20:11,871 --> 00:20:13,838
This tastes better
than the one from this morning.

528
00:20:13,905 --> 00:20:15,605
- It's a higher-quality brand.
- Is it?

529
00:20:15,671 --> 00:20:17,438
UNINTENTIONALLY EVALUATING THE JERKY

530
00:20:17,505 --> 00:20:19,705
While you're here in America,

531
00:20:19,771 --> 00:20:21,738
you need to try different beef jerky.

532
00:20:21,805 --> 00:20:23,271
You'll be impressed.

533
00:20:23,938 --> 00:20:25,638
There's a variety of flavors.

534
00:20:25,705 --> 00:20:29,771
The beef jerky originated in the US.

535
00:20:31,371 --> 00:20:35,138
In the Joseon era,
Koreans dried beef to eat.

536
00:20:35,205 --> 00:20:36,905
JERKY LIKELY ORIGINATED
IN SOUTH AMERICA OR EAST ASIA

537
00:20:36,971 --> 00:20:37,805
SEO-JIN JUST REALLY LOVES AMERICA

538
00:20:37,871 --> 00:20:39,171
Is it good or not?

539
00:20:39,805 --> 00:20:42,738
- [Yung-suk] There he goes again.
- It doesn't get in your teeth.

540
00:20:42,805 --> 00:20:44,905
It's easy to eat.

541
00:20:44,971 --> 00:20:46,305
- It's tender.
- [Yung-suk] That's enough.

542
00:20:46,371 --> 00:20:47,438
CAPTAIN AMERICA ENDS HIS JERKY PREACHING…

543
00:20:47,505 --> 00:20:48,671
[Dae-ju] I can't stand chewy stuff.

544
00:20:48,738 --> 00:20:50,371
[Yung-suk] It's 12:30 a.m. already?

545
00:20:50,438 --> 00:20:53,305
NIGHT FALLS ON THE MOTEL

546
00:20:54,538 --> 00:20:58,205
THE NEXT MORNING

547
00:21:00,105 --> 00:21:01,271
[chuckles]

548
00:21:01,338 --> 00:21:02,671
This tastes good.

549
00:21:02,738 --> 00:21:05,505
AMERICAN-STYLE HANGOVER FOOD WITH CEREAL

550
00:21:05,571 --> 00:21:08,138
- [Dae-ju] Good morning.
- [indistinct chatter]

551
00:21:08,205 --> 00:21:09,205
[staff] Hello.

552
00:21:09,271 --> 00:21:10,771
[Yung-suk] You're here.

553
00:21:10,838 --> 00:21:14,105
A CUP OF COFFEE FOR BREAKFAST

554
00:21:16,938 --> 00:21:19,938
- Ah.
- It's not like you to drink coffee.

555
00:21:21,671 --> 00:21:22,971
I didn't get enough sleep. [chuckles]

556
00:21:23,038 --> 00:21:24,605
- [Dae-ju] Did you not?
- [all laughing]

557
00:21:24,671 --> 00:21:25,871
HE WAS TROUBLED ALL NIGHT

558
00:21:25,938 --> 00:21:29,505
I felt like someone was
sleeping next to me all night

559
00:21:30,338 --> 00:21:32,238
- and woke me up this morning.
- [all laughing]

560
00:21:32,305 --> 00:21:34,938
A STRANGE AND EERIE FEELING

561
00:21:35,005 --> 00:21:36,838
Did you sleep next to the stain?

562
00:21:36,905 --> 00:21:38,605
- I did.
- [all laugh]

563
00:21:38,671 --> 00:21:41,905
Is that why it felt like
someone was next to me?

564
00:21:41,971 --> 00:21:44,538
BELIEVE IT OR NOT
SEO-JIN EASILY GETS SCARED

565
00:21:44,605 --> 00:21:46,505
[Dae-ju] It turns out
there's a farm next door.

566
00:21:46,571 --> 00:21:48,105
We heard the cows all morning. [laughs]

567
00:21:48,171 --> 00:21:49,638
This place has everything you like.

568
00:21:49,705 --> 00:21:51,305
- I should move here.
- [Dae-ju] It's like a ranch.

569
00:21:51,371 --> 00:21:53,771
- It's a ranch with a caravan.
- You should move here.

570
00:21:53,838 --> 00:21:57,271
I told Woo-jung yesterday
that she should write a script here.

571
00:21:57,338 --> 00:21:58,805
IT'S PERFECT FOR WRITING A HIT DRAMA

572
00:21:58,871 --> 00:22:00,105
- [Dae-ju laughs]
- Stay in and write all day.

573
00:22:00,171 --> 00:22:02,505
You'll get a good rate
for a long-term stay.

574
00:22:02,571 --> 00:22:03,738
I bet they'll cut the price.

575
00:22:03,805 --> 00:22:05,971
Yes, use my room. It's big.

576
00:22:06,038 --> 00:22:08,505
- [Woo-jung] I could totally use it.
- Room 100.

577
00:22:08,571 --> 00:22:10,338
- [Yung-suk] You won't feel lonely.
- For sure.

578
00:22:10,405 --> 00:22:13,238
- [Dae-ju laughs]
- I think there are other occupants.

579
00:22:13,305 --> 00:22:14,271
- It's not just one.
- [Yung-suk laughs]

580
00:22:14,338 --> 00:22:16,605
A SHARE HOUSE WHERE YOU WON'T GET LONELY
EVEN MILES FROM HOME

581
00:22:16,671 --> 00:22:18,771
Tex-Mex is a taco place, right?

582
00:22:18,838 --> 00:22:19,738
No, it's not.

583
00:22:19,805 --> 00:22:21,671
- It's not a taco place?
- No, it's not.

584
00:22:21,738 --> 00:22:23,471
It stands for Texas Mexican.

585
00:22:23,538 --> 00:22:25,038
[Yung-suk] Let's go and eat.

586
00:22:25,105 --> 00:22:26,605
OFF TO LUNCH AFTER A HEARTY BREAKFAST

587
00:22:26,671 --> 00:22:27,571
Let's head to Austin.

588
00:22:31,305 --> 00:22:33,005
How great is this?

589
00:22:33,071 --> 00:22:35,171
You can park right in front of your house.

590
00:22:35,238 --> 00:22:36,705
- I love the first floor.
- It's great.

591
00:22:36,771 --> 00:22:39,171
- It's such an advantage.
- It is.

592
00:22:39,238 --> 00:22:42,971
- The guests are delighted with their stay.
- [women laugh]

593
00:22:43,038 --> 00:22:46,338
- I had four slices of bread for breakfast.
- [laughing]

594
00:22:46,405 --> 00:22:48,738
You have to stay in a motel in the US.

595
00:22:48,805 --> 00:22:50,171
[Woo-jung] I loved
being on the first floor.

596
00:22:50,238 --> 00:22:51,638
[Yung-suk]
That's the best choice at a motel.

597
00:22:51,705 --> 00:22:53,205
I'll definitely be back.

598
00:22:53,271 --> 00:22:55,071
LET'S HEAD TO AUSTIN, THE CAPITAL OF TEXAS

599
00:22:56,138 --> 00:22:58,905
There are so many cows here.

600
00:22:58,971 --> 00:23:00,905
Why are they standing in a line?

601
00:23:00,971 --> 00:23:01,971
[Seo-jin] Look at that.

602
00:23:02,038 --> 00:23:03,705
A RUSTIC LANDSCAPE OF GRAZING COWS

603
00:23:03,771 --> 00:23:05,505
It's endless.

604
00:23:05,571 --> 00:23:07,871
There are so many.

605
00:23:07,938 --> 00:23:09,871
They look so content.

606
00:23:09,938 --> 00:23:12,371
- Why wouldn't they be?
- In that wide open field…

607
00:23:12,438 --> 00:23:13,505
JEALOUS

608
00:23:13,571 --> 00:23:17,171
[laughs] Anyone would be happy
running around in an open field.

609
00:23:17,238 --> 00:23:19,438
It must feel even better for animals.

610
00:23:19,505 --> 00:23:22,805
Even as an animal,
you'd want to be born in America.

611
00:23:22,871 --> 00:23:24,771
- [all laughing]
- Don't you think?

612
00:23:24,838 --> 00:23:27,271
SEO-JIN WOULD LIVE HERE EVEN AS AN ANIMAL

613
00:23:27,338 --> 00:23:30,105
- I highly recommend this route to anyone.
- [Woo-jung] I agree.

614
00:23:30,171 --> 00:23:32,105
[Yung-suk] When traveling
from Houston to Austin,

615
00:23:32,171 --> 00:23:34,238
make sure to take
the state highway. [chuckles]

616
00:23:34,305 --> 00:23:35,705
Don't use the expressway.

617
00:23:35,771 --> 00:23:39,171
A REFRESHING HIGHWAY WITH WIDE OPEN FIELDS

618
00:23:39,238 --> 00:23:41,438
There's so much land.

619
00:23:41,505 --> 00:23:45,105
I've never seen so much open space before.

620
00:23:45,871 --> 00:23:50,171
"The US State of Texas
is seven times the size of South Korea."

621
00:23:50,238 --> 00:23:51,805
- It's huge.
- You mean the state?

622
00:23:51,871 --> 00:23:53,305
A SUDDEN LESSON ON TEXAS

623
00:23:53,371 --> 00:23:55,871
"Texas is known
as the world's energy capital,

624
00:23:55,938 --> 00:23:59,071
being one of the leading oil-rich states."

625
00:23:59,138 --> 00:24:03,238
"It has built its prosperity
on blessed oil wealth."

626
00:24:03,305 --> 00:24:05,605
"If Texas were a country,

627
00:24:05,671 --> 00:24:08,605
it would have
the world's eighth largest economy."

628
00:24:09,605 --> 00:24:14,205
"Its economy is already bigger than
Australia and Canada combined."

629
00:24:14,271 --> 00:24:15,271
TEXAS GDP: $2.709 TRILLION IN 2024

630
00:24:15,338 --> 00:24:17,205
CANADA GDP: $2.241 TRILLION
AUSTRALIA GDP: $1.752 TRILLION

631
00:24:17,271 --> 00:24:19,571
The University of Texas
has its own oil fields.

632
00:24:19,638 --> 00:24:20,705
[Woo-jung] Does it really?

633
00:24:20,771 --> 00:24:22,871
They're unbelievably rich.

634
00:24:23,971 --> 00:24:26,605
I want to be
President of the University of Texas.

635
00:24:26,671 --> 00:24:28,505
UNIVERSITY OF TEXAS
TOP PUBLIC INSTITUTION IN THE SOUTH

636
00:24:28,571 --> 00:24:30,838
ALUMNI WHO ARE NOBEL, FIELDS,
TURING, AND PULITZER PRIZE WINNERS

637
00:24:30,905 --> 00:24:34,505
ITS SYMBOLS INCLUDE THE LONGHORN LOGO
AND THE BURNT ORANGE COLOR

638
00:24:34,571 --> 00:24:37,338
[Woo-jung] Do you need to be smart
to graduate from UT?

639
00:24:37,405 --> 00:24:39,038
- [Yung-suk] Probably.
- Of course.

640
00:24:39,105 --> 00:24:40,805
Matthew McConaughey went there.

641
00:24:40,871 --> 00:24:42,971
Yes, the one in Austin.

642
00:24:43,038 --> 00:24:46,971
He sometimes goes to football games
at the university.

643
00:24:47,038 --> 00:24:52,238
Whenever there's a game,
they show him cheering on the big screen.

644
00:24:52,305 --> 00:24:53,405
Fans must go crazy.

645
00:24:53,471 --> 00:24:55,471
You'll see him wearing the cowboy hat,

646
00:24:55,538 --> 00:24:57,871
jeans, Western boots,
and a leather jacket.

647
00:24:57,938 --> 00:24:59,805
- We can do that too, can't we?
- [Seo-jin] What?

648
00:25:01,771 --> 00:25:04,138
- We would be dragged out of there.
- [both laugh]

649
00:25:04,205 --> 00:25:06,505
SELF-AWARENESS SEEMS TO BE WORKING

650
00:25:07,438 --> 00:25:10,638
2 HOURS OF DRIVING AND ENDLESS CHATTING…

651
00:25:11,205 --> 00:25:13,638
- I think that's Austin.
- [upbeat music plays]

652
00:25:13,705 --> 00:25:15,971
AUSTIN ON THE HORIZON!

653
00:25:16,705 --> 00:25:18,905
THE CAPITAL OF TEXAS

654
00:25:18,971 --> 00:25:21,971
AUSTIN

655
00:25:22,038 --> 00:25:25,971
BEST CAPITAL TO LIVE IN,
ACCORDING TO WALLETHUB 2025

656
00:25:26,538 --> 00:25:27,638
A RISING TECHNOLOGY HOTSPOT

657
00:25:27,705 --> 00:25:30,138
HOME TO GLOBAL GIANTS
SUCH AS TESLA'S HEADQUARTERS AND GOOGLE

658
00:25:30,205 --> 00:25:34,138
TRUE TO ITS SLOGAN "KEEP AUSTIN WEIRD,"

659
00:25:34,205 --> 00:25:38,205
IT'S DIVERSE, FREE-SPIRITED,
AND FULL OF LIFE

660
00:25:38,271 --> 00:25:41,838
OFF TO HAVE LUNCH AT A RESTAURANT
ON THE OUTSKIRTS OF AUSTIN!

661
00:25:41,905 --> 00:25:45,538
YAWN

662
00:25:48,105 --> 00:25:50,071
Do you have to pay royalties for hymns?

663
00:25:50,138 --> 00:25:51,405
WHAT THAT MEANS IS…

664
00:25:51,471 --> 00:25:52,571
- [both laugh]
- Probably not.

665
00:25:52,638 --> 00:25:56,105
- You can't give money to a divine being.
- Aren't they under copyright?

666
00:25:56,171 --> 00:25:58,738
DUE TO COPYRIGHT,
THEY WERE TOLD NOT TO PLAY ANY MUSIC

667
00:25:58,805 --> 00:26:04,205
We've been driving for ten hours,
and we can't listen to any music.

668
00:26:04,271 --> 00:26:06,238
IT CAN GET BORING

669
00:26:06,305 --> 00:26:08,738
How about a verse
from "The Song of Chunhyang"?

670
00:26:08,805 --> 00:26:10,905
[Yung-suk] Please sing it for us.

671
00:26:10,971 --> 00:26:13,071
THE COPYRIGHT-FREE KOREAN FOLK CHANT
"SSUKDAEMEORI"

672
00:26:13,138 --> 00:26:14,838
- "Ssukdaemeori"?
- Yes.

673
00:26:14,905 --> 00:26:17,638
♪ <i>Ssukdaemeori</i> ♪

674
00:26:17,705 --> 00:26:18,538
Is that it?

675
00:26:18,605 --> 00:26:21,005
♪ <i>A ghostly appearance…</i> ♪

676
00:26:21,071 --> 00:26:25,005
- Ye-seul, do you have the playlist?
- [Dae-ju] She does.

677
00:26:25,071 --> 00:26:27,171
- Should I play it?
- Go ahead.

678
00:26:27,238 --> 00:26:29,105
- Let's put something on.
- Yes.

679
00:26:29,771 --> 00:26:31,871
- I can't take it anymore.
- [all laughing]

680
00:26:31,938 --> 00:26:34,038
HE CAN'T HANDLE DRIVING WITHOUT MUSIC

681
00:26:34,105 --> 00:26:36,005
PLAYLIST LOADING

682
00:26:36,071 --> 00:26:38,105
This place feels like Spain.

683
00:26:38,171 --> 00:26:41,105
- Hurry up. I'm tired of hearing Dae-ju.
- [all laughing]

684
00:26:41,171 --> 00:26:42,638
[upbeat song playing]

685
00:26:42,705 --> 00:26:44,505
THE MUSIC COMES ON AT PERFECT TIMING

686
00:26:44,571 --> 00:26:46,671
- This is so much better.
- Does it have singing too?

687
00:26:46,738 --> 00:26:48,471
LIMITED PLAYLIST

688
00:26:48,538 --> 00:26:51,238
Netflix makes great music.

689
00:26:51,305 --> 00:26:53,405
NETFLIX JUST GOT THE LICENSE

690
00:26:53,971 --> 00:26:56,471
DRIVING ALONG, LISTENING TO MUSIC
FOR THE FIRST TIME IN TEXAS

691
00:26:58,205 --> 00:26:59,505
ARRIVED AT TODAY'S LUNCH SPOT!

692
00:26:59,571 --> 00:27:02,005
- It reminds me of Jangheung Resort.
- [Yung-suk] It does.

693
00:27:02,071 --> 00:27:03,838
It says "Oasis. Welcome."

694
00:27:03,905 --> 00:27:05,971
[country music playing]

695
00:27:08,338 --> 00:27:10,471
ENTERING

696
00:27:11,005 --> 00:27:12,171
What do we do with the music?

697
00:27:12,238 --> 00:27:13,871
- Funny vibe.
- The music is playing.

698
00:27:13,938 --> 00:27:15,405
MUSIC REPLACED DUE TO COPYRIGHT

699
00:27:15,471 --> 00:27:17,071
- What about this music?
- Such a fun vibe!

700
00:27:20,238 --> 00:27:21,605
[Yung-suk] It's a really fun vibe.

701
00:27:21,671 --> 00:27:23,838
AN INTERIOR THAT BRINGS
FORGOTTEN VALUES BACK TO LIFE

702
00:27:23,905 --> 00:27:25,905
It smells good, Seo-jin.

703
00:27:25,971 --> 00:27:27,005
It does smells good.

704
00:27:27,071 --> 00:27:28,338
I bet it tastes great.

705
00:27:29,071 --> 00:27:30,705
Look at this view.

706
00:27:30,771 --> 00:27:33,205
EYE-CATCHING VIEW AS SOON AS YOU WALK IN

707
00:27:33,271 --> 00:27:34,538
Look at that.

708
00:27:35,471 --> 00:27:36,971
A REFRESHING LAKE VIEW

709
00:27:37,038 --> 00:27:38,805
This is a place worth the trip.

710
00:27:40,771 --> 00:27:43,638
A POPULAR TOURIST PHOTO SPOT

711
00:27:43,705 --> 00:27:46,571
A PLACE FOR ETERNAL LOVE VOWS…

712
00:27:46,638 --> 00:27:48,971
AND THE REASON FOR THIS VISIT

713
00:27:49,038 --> 00:27:50,071
[Yung-suk] Oasis…

714
00:27:50,138 --> 00:27:51,505
It smells so good.

715
00:27:52,071 --> 00:27:53,071
This is the Tex-Mex.

716
00:27:53,138 --> 00:27:56,171
TEXAN-STYLE MEXICAN CUISINE
MADE WITH CHEESE, CHILI, AND TORTILLAS

717
00:27:56,805 --> 00:27:59,305
A TREAT FOR THE EYES AND MOUTH

718
00:27:59,371 --> 00:28:01,538
It smells really good. I'm excited.

719
00:28:01,605 --> 00:28:02,871
[Woo-jung] It's just our style.

720
00:28:02,938 --> 00:28:05,538
<i>♪ I'm looking forward to this… ♪</i>

721
00:28:05,605 --> 00:28:06,471
We have to…

722
00:28:06,538 --> 00:28:07,571
SCAN THE QR CODE TO ORDER

723
00:28:07,638 --> 00:28:10,405
- [Woo-jung] He'll order for us, right?
- We have to scan the code.

724
00:28:10,971 --> 00:28:13,705
The text is too small for you to read.

725
00:28:14,471 --> 00:28:15,671
- You mean the menu?
- Yes.

726
00:28:15,738 --> 00:28:17,905
- Can you read it?
- Zoom in.

727
00:28:18,471 --> 00:28:20,371
I thought you wanted Tex-Mex?

728
00:28:20,438 --> 00:28:22,905
Shouldn't we order a variety of dishes?

729
00:28:22,971 --> 00:28:25,338
A VARIETY TO TASTE A BIT OF EVERYTHING!

730
00:28:25,405 --> 00:28:28,138
- [Woo-jung] It's here.
- [in English] Thank you.

731
00:28:28,771 --> 00:28:31,871
[in Korean] He's going to lick
his fingers again.

732
00:28:31,938 --> 00:28:33,271
Shouldn't you wash them first?

733
00:28:33,338 --> 00:28:34,871
[Ye-seul] Do you want some wet wipes?

734
00:28:34,938 --> 00:28:38,038
A SIDE OF GUACAMOLE

735
00:28:38,105 --> 00:28:38,938
In the morning…

736
00:28:39,005 --> 00:28:39,838
I WASHED UP

737
00:28:39,905 --> 00:28:41,871
That was hours ago.

738
00:28:41,938 --> 00:28:44,038
- [Woo-jung] A staff member had wet wipes.
- Thank you.

739
00:28:44,105 --> 00:28:46,271
SEO-JIN WENT TO THE RESTROOM
YUNG-SUK USED WET WIPES

740
00:28:47,005 --> 00:28:51,238
DIGGING INTO THE NACHOS WITH CLEAN HANDS

741
00:28:51,305 --> 00:28:53,905
This is pretty spicy.

742
00:28:53,971 --> 00:28:55,971
I thought Americans
were bad with spicy food.

743
00:28:56,038 --> 00:28:57,671
But Mexican food is usually spicy.

744
00:28:57,738 --> 00:29:00,571
- They do like spicy food.
- [Woo-jung] It is spicy.

745
00:29:00,638 --> 00:29:01,871
Try this.

746
00:29:03,671 --> 00:29:06,771
WITH A NICE BIG SCOOP OF GUACAMOLE

747
00:29:06,838 --> 00:29:08,505
[Woo-jung] This avocado is delicious.

748
00:29:09,071 --> 00:29:10,338
[Yung-suk] It's good, isn't it?

749
00:29:10,405 --> 00:29:11,671
YES

750
00:29:12,171 --> 00:29:13,371
The guacamole is a must.

751
00:29:13,438 --> 00:29:14,705
THE PERFECT FOOD PAIRING

752
00:29:14,771 --> 00:29:17,905
[Woo-jung] You had a lot of Mexican food
in college, right?

753
00:29:17,971 --> 00:29:20,438
During vacations,
my friends and I would get together,

754
00:29:20,505 --> 00:29:23,171
lay out 200 tacos on the table,

755
00:29:23,238 --> 00:29:25,771
and grab one whenever we felt like it.

756
00:29:25,838 --> 00:29:27,338
How do you even buy 200 tacos?

757
00:29:27,405 --> 00:29:28,405
FASCINATED

758
00:29:28,471 --> 00:29:30,805
- Can you order that many?
- Yes.

759
00:29:30,871 --> 00:29:35,105
I used to order ten tacos at once
at places like Taco Bell.

760
00:29:35,805 --> 00:29:37,405
You must have liked them, right?

761
00:29:38,005 --> 00:29:40,271
- I wasn't being forced to eat it.
- [all laughing]

762
00:29:40,338 --> 00:29:41,571
But you're not a big foodie.

763
00:29:41,638 --> 00:29:43,671
- For you to have ten tacos…
- [Woo-jung] That's a lot for you.

764
00:29:43,738 --> 00:29:45,938
I used to have a bigger appetite.

765
00:29:46,505 --> 00:29:47,705
There it is.

766
00:29:47,771 --> 00:29:48,638
What is it?

767
00:29:50,338 --> 00:29:52,038
[Woo-jung] It's a bowl.
I ordered the beef.

768
00:29:52,105 --> 00:29:53,205
FIRST DISH OF THE MAIN MENU

769
00:29:53,271 --> 00:29:54,105
It's nice and hot.

770
00:29:54,171 --> 00:29:55,905
[server in English]
This here will be your shrimp taco.

771
00:29:56,471 --> 00:29:57,738
[Woo-jung] That's a full plate.

772
00:29:57,805 --> 00:29:59,138
FAJITA
IT'S A CLASSIC TEX-MEX DISH

773
00:29:59,205 --> 00:30:01,238
GRILLED MEAT, SEAFOOD,
OR VEGGIES WRAPPED IN TORTILLA

774
00:30:01,305 --> 00:30:02,938
Can I have a piece of that taco?

775
00:30:03,005 --> 00:30:04,538
- This one?
- [Woo-jung] Burrito or taco?

776
00:30:04,605 --> 00:30:05,738
- You want the burrito?
- Yes.

777
00:30:05,805 --> 00:30:07,238
ENCHILADA
TORTILLA FILLED AND BAKED IN THE OVEN

778
00:30:07,305 --> 00:30:09,138
[Yung-suk] It looks really good.
Hand it over.

779
00:30:09,205 --> 00:30:11,171
I'll dish some out for him.

780
00:30:11,238 --> 00:30:12,371
- What's this?
- This is it.

781
00:30:12,438 --> 00:30:14,071
Is it chili?

782
00:30:14,138 --> 00:30:15,805
It looks like chili con carne.

783
00:30:15,871 --> 00:30:17,138
This is something I like.

784
00:30:18,038 --> 00:30:22,105
This takes me back to my days in KATUSA.

785
00:30:22,171 --> 00:30:23,738
CHILI CON CARNE
IT MEANS CHILI WITH MEAT

786
00:30:23,805 --> 00:30:25,605
SPICY STEW MADE BY BOILING
BEEF, KIDNEY BEANS, AND ONIONS

787
00:30:25,671 --> 00:30:27,238
THE FOOD YUNG-SUK LOVED IN THE MILITARY

788
00:30:27,305 --> 00:30:29,138
It's really tasty.

789
00:30:29,205 --> 00:30:31,738
SEO-JIN IS ALSO RELISHING IT

790
00:30:31,805 --> 00:30:33,171
It's filled with rice.

791
00:30:33,238 --> 00:30:36,371
[Yung-suk] This bowl
is an all-in-one experience.

792
00:30:37,038 --> 00:30:39,205
I prefer it not mixed.

793
00:30:39,271 --> 00:30:40,205
CHEWING AWAY

794
00:30:40,271 --> 00:30:41,805
Oh, wait. It's really good.

795
00:30:41,871 --> 00:30:43,405
- It's tasty.
- It is.

796
00:30:43,471 --> 00:30:45,071
It's basically the same thing.

797
00:30:45,571 --> 00:30:47,671
I'm making my own taco.

798
00:30:47,738 --> 00:30:49,305
TIME TO MAKE TACOS

799
00:30:50,505 --> 00:30:52,138
BRUSHING OFF THE CRUMBS

800
00:30:52,205 --> 00:30:54,838
Why would you brush them off
into your food?

801
00:30:54,905 --> 00:30:58,005
The food here at Tex-Mex is made for me.

802
00:30:58,071 --> 00:30:59,671
You have to use your hands.

803
00:30:59,738 --> 00:31:03,305
- You'll end up licking all your fingers.
- [all laughing]

804
00:31:05,638 --> 00:31:07,105
You're having mostly chicken.

805
00:31:07,171 --> 00:31:08,571
LET'S SEE HOW SEO-JIN MAKES A TACO

806
00:31:08,638 --> 00:31:10,705
- Are you on a diet?
- I just want the meat.

807
00:31:10,771 --> 00:31:11,971
LEE SEO-JIN'S TACO RECIPE

808
00:31:12,038 --> 00:31:13,405
1. PILE UP MEAT ON A TORTILLA

809
00:31:13,471 --> 00:31:15,305
[Yung-suk]
Like a Korean-style lettuce wrap.

810
00:31:15,371 --> 00:31:16,538
2. BALANCE IT WITH VEGETABLES

811
00:31:16,605 --> 00:31:18,971
It's a matter of preference
whether you add sauce or not.

812
00:31:19,038 --> 00:31:24,338
3. ADD A TOUCH OF SPICE WITH CHILI SAUCE

813
00:31:26,338 --> 00:31:29,471
4. OPEN WIDE AND TAKE A BIG BITE

814
00:31:30,905 --> 00:31:32,471
SATISFIED

815
00:31:32,538 --> 00:31:34,505
The chicken is my favorite.

816
00:31:35,171 --> 00:31:37,605
They know how to grill their meat.

817
00:31:38,438 --> 00:31:39,605
But you know…

818
00:31:41,038 --> 00:31:43,238
We tried Mexican food in <i>Jinny's Kitchen.</i>

819
00:31:43,305 --> 00:31:45,138
Remember the local market food?

820
00:31:45,705 --> 00:31:47,538
Locals don't go to all this trouble.

821
00:31:47,605 --> 00:31:50,538
I think American culture influenced it.

822
00:31:51,171 --> 00:31:52,705
In Mexico,

823
00:31:52,771 --> 00:31:56,705
they put meat on a thin pancake
and dip it in sauce.

824
00:31:56,771 --> 00:31:58,005
But it tastes great.

825
00:31:59,505 --> 00:32:00,705
I'm enjoying all this food.

826
00:32:00,771 --> 00:32:02,238
EVERYBODY IS ENJOYING THE MEAL WHEN…

827
00:32:02,305 --> 00:32:04,071
Goodness, that's not how…

828
00:32:04,138 --> 00:32:07,038
- You're supposed to wrap it.
- [staff 1 laughs]

829
00:32:07,105 --> 00:32:08,371
- Don't you know tacos?
- [laughs]

830
00:32:08,438 --> 00:32:11,038
- [staff 2] Why are you using a knife?
- [Seo-jin] How is she eating them?

831
00:32:11,105 --> 00:32:12,871
- It seemed like I should cut them.
- [Seo-jin] What?

832
00:32:12,938 --> 00:32:15,271
[Woo-jung] Ju-yeong
is sitting so lifelessly.

833
00:32:15,338 --> 00:32:16,971
[laughs] Totally.

834
00:32:17,038 --> 00:32:18,738
[Woo-jung] She's like
a student in trouble.

835
00:32:19,405 --> 00:32:21,571
- What?
- I'm enjoying the meal.

836
00:32:21,638 --> 00:32:23,405
[Woo-jung] How old are you, Ju-yeong?

837
00:32:23,471 --> 00:32:25,538
- [Ju-yeong] I was born in 1998.
- [Woo-jung] In 1998?

838
00:32:25,605 --> 00:32:26,771
How old is your father?

839
00:32:27,305 --> 00:32:28,971
- [Ju-yeong] He was born in 1968.
- In 1968?

840
00:32:29,038 --> 00:32:29,871
HIS FACE LIGHTS UP

841
00:32:29,938 --> 00:32:30,938
[Woo-jung] He's relieved.

842
00:32:31,005 --> 00:32:32,138
LEE SEO-JIN WAS BORN IN 1971

843
00:32:32,205 --> 00:32:34,671
- [all laugh]
- [Woo-jung] It's a relief, right?

844
00:32:40,171 --> 00:32:42,205
What's in your pocket?

845
00:32:43,938 --> 00:32:45,605
I don't know.

846
00:32:45,671 --> 00:32:47,005
A STRANGE DISCOVERY IN HER POCKET

847
00:32:47,071 --> 00:32:48,105
What is it?

848
00:32:48,605 --> 00:32:50,371
It's spilling out of your pocket.

849
00:32:50,438 --> 00:32:52,038
Looks like this. [laughs]

850
00:32:52,871 --> 00:32:54,771
Hey, she really is one of your colleagues.

851
00:32:54,838 --> 00:32:56,071
- Why?
- She's a messy eater.

852
00:32:56,138 --> 00:32:57,438
[staff] Why did you drop so much food?

853
00:32:57,505 --> 00:32:59,605
Vegetables are spilling out of her pocket.

854
00:32:59,671 --> 00:33:01,005
[all laughing]

855
00:33:01,071 --> 00:33:03,171
THE EGG IS COMING STAFF
SPILL FOOD JUST LIKE YUNG-SUK

856
00:33:03,238 --> 00:33:04,971
Her pants are a mess.

857
00:33:05,105 --> 00:33:07,505
- Are you keeping it for later?
- Look at this big chunk.

858
00:33:07,571 --> 00:33:08,771
Are you taking home leftovers?

859
00:33:08,838 --> 00:33:10,838
[Seo-jin] This big chunk
fell out of her pocket.

860
00:33:11,371 --> 00:33:13,071
I almost picked it up.

861
00:33:13,138 --> 00:33:14,971
Jeez, there's more here.

862
00:33:15,038 --> 00:33:16,905
Have you been rolling around in food?

863
00:33:16,971 --> 00:33:18,871
CONCERNED ABOUT HER
AS SOMEONE NOT MUCH OLDER THAN HER DAD

864
00:33:18,938 --> 00:33:21,771
- She got it all over the surface.
- [Woo-jung] Did she drop more food?

865
00:33:21,838 --> 00:33:24,005
You are that kind of person.
You made her feel nervous.

866
00:33:24,071 --> 00:33:27,138
- He said "surface," not "nervous."
- [all laughing]

867
00:33:27,205 --> 00:33:28,705
DID THE PRODUCTION TEAM
MAKE A MESS ON THE SURFACE?

868
00:33:28,771 --> 00:33:29,971
DID THE PRODUCTION TEAM FEEL NERVOUS?

869
00:33:30,871 --> 00:33:33,238
We've cleaned up nicely.

870
00:33:33,905 --> 00:33:35,238
Are you done?

871
00:33:35,305 --> 00:33:36,905
[Ju-yeong] Yes, I'm full.

872
00:33:36,971 --> 00:33:38,205
Do you want some beer?

873
00:33:38,271 --> 00:33:39,105
OFFERS WITH A FATHERLY HEART

874
00:33:39,171 --> 00:33:40,171
Let's have some beer.

875
00:33:40,238 --> 00:33:41,705
Should we go? But where?

876
00:33:41,771 --> 00:33:44,338
- Let's first decide where to go.
- [staff] Let's look around.

877
00:33:44,405 --> 00:33:46,771
Do you want to put up a friendship lock?

878
00:33:46,838 --> 00:33:47,838
A friendship lock?

879
00:33:47,905 --> 00:33:50,471
- [staff] I mean the lock outside.
- Give me one. Let's do it.

880
00:33:50,538 --> 00:33:53,571
I want to take down the hanging ones.
What are you talking about?

881
00:33:53,638 --> 00:33:56,771
- Forget it.
- [Yung-suk laughing]

882
00:33:56,838 --> 00:33:58,238
Let's get going.

883
00:33:58,305 --> 00:33:59,505
[Seo-jin] It's too cold.

884
00:33:59,571 --> 00:34:01,938
A FRIENDSHIP TRIP THAT NEEDS NO LOCKS
TO BE CONTINUED…

885
00:34:02,005 --> 00:34:04,005
[country music playing]

886
00:34:47,771 --> 00:34:52,771
Subtitle translation by: Hannah Og Nam
